    "translations": {
      "en": {
        "summary": "Imam al-Sadiq (peace be upon him) narrates two accounts demonstrating the exemplary practice of manual labor by the Imams: Imam Ali (AS) digging and cultivating lands with a hoe, and Prophet Muhammad (SAWW) planting date pits that sprouted miraculously within the hour. The tradition further records that Imam Ali freed one thousand slaves from earnings of his own physical labor — illustrating that Islamic leadership demands personal engagement in honest work and that the fruits of one's livelihood must be earned through one's own hands before being devoted to charitable ends.",
        "key_terms": {
          "الْمَرّ": "A hoe or mattock, the primary agricultural digging implement of early Arabia",
          "النَّوَى": "Date pits/seeds — planting them was a common act of charity and cultivation",
          "كَدّ الْيَد": "Toil of the hand — a classical expression for manual earnings, stressing the dignity of physical labor",
          "مَمْلُوك": "A person in bondage; freeing (i'taq) a slave was among the highest acts of virtue"
        },
        "seo_question": "What did Imam Ali do to earn money for freeing slaves according to al-Kafi?"
